`crates/` is the workspace root containing six independent binary/lib crates that together form the ctx system: generate, verify, sandbox-execute, scan, and brief-generate a repository's context documentation. There is no shared code across crates at this level — `ctx-core` is the only shared kernel, consumed by `ctx-scan` and `ctx-context`; the rest (`ctx-summarize`, `ctx-verify`, `ctx-cage`, `ctx-brief`) are standalone with no cross-crate Rust dependencies.

The crates divide cleanly by lifecycle stage and are meant to be composed via subprocess/file boundaries, not linked: `ctx-summarize` writes `.ctx`/`rollup.ctx` files from an LLM agent; `ctx-context` reads that same chain read-only and serves/injects it, never writing; `ctx-scan` independently tracks staleness via its own `.context` mirror layout, which `ctx-summarize` also touches — both crates duplicate awareness of the `.context` mirror-path convention, so a layout change must be checked in both `ctx-summarize/src` and `ctx-scan/src`. `ctx-verify` and `ctx-cage` run checks/sandboxes over a repo; `ctx-brief` drives `claude` CLI passes to turn asks into executor briefs. None of these crates' rollups mention a shared prompt format or wire protocol beyond that `.context` convention.

Each crate enforces its own internal contracts (trait seams, status precedence, rollup ordering) independently — no invariant spans crate boundaries here except the `.context` mirror convention. A typical cross-crate change (e.g., altering how staleness or rollup paths are laid out) touches `ctx-summarize` and `ctx-scan` together; everything else is single-crate work.

No `intent.md` exists at this level, so no divergence check applies.